{"id":"1210.8138","submitter":"Martin Bojowald","authors":"Martin Bojowald, Alexander L. Chinchilli, Christine C. Dantas, Matthew\n  Jaffe and David Simpson","title":"Non-linear (loop) quantum cosmology","comments":"20 pages","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. D 86 (2012) 124027","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.86.124027","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Inhomogeneous quantum cosmology is modeled as a dynamical system of discrete\npatches, whose interacting many-body equations can be mapped to a non-linear\nminisuperspace equation by methods analogous to Bose-Einstein condensation.\nComplicated gravitational dynamics can therefore be described by\nmore-manageable equations for finitely many degrees of freedom, for which\npowerful solution procedures are available, including effective equations. The\nspecific form of non-linear and non-local equations suggests new questions for\nmathematical and computational investigations, and general properties of\nnon-linear wave equations lead to several new options for physical effects and\ntests of the consistency of loop quantum gravity. In particular, our quantum\ncosmological methods show how sizeable quantum corrections in a low-curvature\nuniverse can arise from tiny local contributions adding up coherently in large\nregions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 30 Oct 2012 19:50:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-12-18"}
{"id":"1210.8139","submitter":"Scott Provan","authors":"J. Scott Provan, Marcus Brazil, Doreen Thomas, Jia F. Weng","title":"Minimum Opaque Covers for Polygonal Regions","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Opaque Cover Problem (OCP), also known as the Beam Detector Problem, is\nthe problem of finding, for a set S in Euclidean space, the minimum-length set\nF which intersects every straight line passing through S. In spite of its\nsimplicity, the problem remains remarkably intractable. The aim of this paper\nis to establish a framework and fundamental results for minimum opaque covers\nwhere S is a polygonal region in two-dimensional space. We begin by giving some\ngeneral results about opaque covers, and describe the close connection that the\nOCP has with the Point Goalie Problem. We then consider properties of graphical\nsolutions to the OCP when S is a convex polygonal region in the plane.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 30 Oct 2012 19:52:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-10-31"}
